# Just Bloom Spa — Cursor Rules
# These rules govern every file generated or edited in this codebase.
# Read this entire file before writing any code.

---

## 1. Project Overview

Just Bloom Spa is a **100% offline, desktop-first Progressive Web App (PWA)** for managing a single-location spa in Accra, Ghana. It handles transactions, customers, staff, reporting, and end-of-day reconciliation. Data is stored locally using **SQLite WASM** persisted to the **Origin Private File System (OPFS)**. There is no backend server, no cloud sync, and no external API calls (except CDN assets on first load).

**Brand:** Just Bloom Spa · Deep forest green · Warm cream · Gold accents · Lotus motif  
**Currency:** GHS (Ghanaian Cedi)  
**Users:** Staff, Manager, Owner (3-tier role hierarchy)

---

## 2. Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|---|---|
| Framework | React 18 + TypeScript (strict) |
| Build tool | Vite |
| PWA | vite-plugin-pwa + Workbox |
| Styling | Tailwind CSS v3 + custom design tokens |
| Components | shadcn/ui (customised to brand) |
| State | Zustand |
| Forms | React Hook Form + Zod |
| Charts | Recharts |
| Routing | React Router v6 |
| Database | @sqlite.org/sqlite-wasm (OPFS persistence) |
| Auth | bcryptjs (in-browser password hashing) |
| Print | react-to-print |
| Linting | ESLint + Prettier |
| Testing | Vitest + React Testing Library |

---

## 3. Architecture Principles

### 3.1 SOLID — enforced at every layer

**Single Responsibility Principle**
- Every file exports exactly one primary concern.
- A component renders UI only — no business logic, no direct DB calls.
- A service handles business logic only — no UI concerns, no direct store mutations.
- A repository handles data access only — no business logic.
- A hook composes one logical behaviour — not a kitchen-sink utility.

**Open/Closed Principle**
- Extend functionality via new modules, not by modifying existing ones.
- Use TypeScript interfaces as extension points. Implementations are closed to modification.
- Add new report types by implementing `IReport`, not by editing `ReportService`.

**Liskov Substitution Principle**
- Any class implementing an interface must fully honour the contract.
- Never throw in a method that the interface promises will return a value.
- Repository implementations must be interchangeable.

**Interface Segregation Principle**
- Prefer many small, focused interfaces over one large one.
- A `CustomerRepository` interface must not include methods only relevant to `TransactionRepository`.
- Props interfaces must be split when a component is used in multiple contexts.

**Dependency Inversion Principle**
- High-level modules (services) depend on interfaces, not concrete implementations.
- Inject dependencies via constructor or React context — never import concrete classes directly into services.
- Example: `TransactionService` depends on `ITransactionRepository`, not `SqliteTransactionRepository`.

### 3.2 Additional architecture standards

- **Clean Architecture layers:** UI → State → Service → Repository → Database. Each layer may only call the layer directly below it.
- **Feature isolation:** Features must not import directly from other features. Cross-feature communication goes through shared stores or shared services.
- **Pure functions first:** Default to pure, side-effect-free functions. Side effects are isolated to services, stores, and hooks.
- **Immutability:** Never mutate objects or arrays in place. Always return new copies.
- **Fail fast:** Validate inputs at the boundary (form layer + Zod). Never pass invalid data into a service.

